“If I Did Not Write about Torture and Abuse at the Hands of the US Government, They Might Think That I Am Consenting to it.”
That is the Clinical Psychosis of Torturers That I Am Confronting.
The belief that a torture victim’s silence constitutes consent is not an incidental feature of the perpetrator’s psychology. It is a load-bearing element of the cognitive architecture that makes sustained torture possible.
Read it again with fresh eyes.
“If I did not write about torture and abuse at the hands of the US government, they might think that I am consenting to it. That is the clinical psychosis of torturers that I am confronting.”
The psychosis is theirs. The “they” who might think he is consenting — the operators, the handlers, the people running the program — are the ones Pearson is diagnosing. He is saying: the people doing this to me are operating from a psychological framework so distorted that they would interpret my silence as consent. And that distortion — the belief system that makes silence equal consent in the mind of a torturer — is itself a clinical condition. A psychosis. And it is the psychosis he has to navigate every day, because it governs the behavior of the people who have power over his life.
This is a much more precise and much more devastating observation than anything about his own psychology. He is not describing his trauma. He is describing their pathology.


The Torturer’s Psychology: What the Literature Establishes
The clinical and psychological literature on perpetrators of state-sanctioned torture is specific about the cognitive and moral frameworks that make sustained torture possible. It is not, primarily, a literature about sadism. Sadism — the enjoyment of cruelty for its own sake — is relatively rare even among documented perpetrators of systematic abuse. What the literature documents instead is a set of cognitive distortions that are far more mundane, far more stable, and far more dangerous precisely because they do not feel, to the person holding them, like distortions at all.
James Waller’s work in Becoming Evil establishes that ordinary people become capable of extraordinary cruelty through a specific psychological pathway: the dehumanization of the target, the diffusion of individual responsibility across an institutional structure, the authorization of conduct by legitimate-seeming authority, and the routinization of harm through bureaucratic procedure. Each of these mechanisms operates to sever the perpetrator’s normal empathic response to the suffering they cause. The harm becomes procedural rather than personal. The target becomes a category rather than a person. The perpetrator becomes a functionary rather than an agent.
But Waller’s framework, while accurate, does not capture the specific distortion Pearson is identifying. He is not simply saying his torturers have dehumanized him or diffused their responsibility. He is saying something more precise: they have a theory of consent that is psychotic.

The Consent Psychosis
The belief that a torture victim’s silence constitutes consent is not an incidental feature of the perpetrator’s psychology. It is a load-bearing element of the cognitive architecture that makes sustained torture possible.
Consider what it would mean for a torturer to genuinely reckon with the absence of consent in their victim. It would mean acknowledging that the harm they are inflicting is being inflicted on a person who is resisting it, who experiences it as harm, who has not agreed to it, and who is being denied the ability to refuse it. That acknowledgment, held honestly, produces a moral reality that is incompatible with continuing. The torturer who genuinely sees the victim’s non-consent cannot continue without accepting the full weight of what they are doing.
The psychosis Pearson identifies is the cognitive mechanism that prevents this reckoning. The belief — held with the rigidity and imperviousness to evidence that defines delusional thinking — that the victim who does not loudly, persistently, and visibly resist is not really a victim. That silence is agreement. That accommodation is acceptance. That the person who has been broken into compliance has revealed, through their compliance, that the targeting was appropriate. That the target who stops fighting has confirmed the designation.
This is psychotic in the clinical sense because it inverts the causal relationship between the harm and the response to the harm. The torture produces the silence. The silence is then read as evidence that the torture was justified. The perpetrator’s conduct is retroactively validated by the outcome that conduct was specifically designed to produce. The distortion is self-sealing. It cannot be falsified by any behavior the victim exhibits, because every possible behavior — resistance and silence alike — is absorbed into the framework that confirms the perpetrator’s position.

The Authorization Framework and Moral Disengagement
Albert Bandura’s theory of moral disengagement provides the clinical scaffolding for understanding how otherwise functional people maintain this distortion over time without experiencing it as distortion.
Moral disengagement operates through eight specific mechanisms, several of which are directly relevant to what Pearson is describing. Moral justification converts harmful conduct into service of a higher purpose — the target is a threat to national security, a Black Identity Extremist, a destabilizing force whose neutralization protects the social order. Dehumanization strips the target of the psychological qualities that activate empathic response — the target is a category, a designation, a file number, not a person with a PhD and a dissertation and a life. Diffusion of responsibility distributes the conduct across so many institutional actors that no single person experiences themselves as the agent of the harm. And advantageous comparison makes the conduct seem reasonable by reference to worse conduct — we are not doing what the Soviets did, we are merely managing a threat.
But the most relevant mechanism for Pearson’s observation is what Bandura calls displacement of responsibility — the cognitive operation by which the perpetrator locates the cause of the harm in the victim’s own conduct. You brought this on yourself. Your work was a threat. Your silence would end this. Your resistance is why this continues.
The displacement of responsibility onto the victim is the precise mechanism that generates the consent interpretation Pearson is describing. If the victim is responsible for the targeting, then the victim controls the targeting. If the victim controls the targeting, then the victim who continues to be targeted has, in some sense, chosen to be targeted. And the victim who stops writing, stops documenting, stops publicly naming what is being done — has chosen to stop provoking it. Has consented to the terms. Has acknowledged, through silence, the legitimacy of the designation.
This is not a metaphor. This is the actual cognitive structure through which people who conduct sustained targeting programs experience what they are doing as something other than what it is. It is the psychosis Pearson lives inside, because it governs the operational logic of the people who have the power to intensify or withdraw the pressure being applied to his life.

The Specific Danger This Creates
Understanding this as their clinical profile rather than his own illuminates something important about the strategic logic of Pearson’s writing.
If the perpetrators operate from a framework in which silence equals consent, then silence does not merely fail to protect him. It actively informs the program’s operational decisions. A target who goes quiet has, within the perpetrators’ framework, been successfully neutralized. The pressure has worked. The designation has been validated. The program can either de-escalate — mission accomplished — or escalate, now confident that the target’s resistance has been broken and further pressure will meet no organized opposition.
Pearson writing is therefore not just the maintenance of his own witnessing self. It is a direct communication to the perpetrators, within the only framework they understand, that the program has not achieved its objective. That the consent their psychosis requires has not been given. That the designation they have applied has not been internalized. That the target is still a witness, still a researcher, still a person whose moral reality is intact and whose account of events is being maintained in a form that cannot be classified, suppressed, or reinterpreted through psychiatric attribution.
He is not writing for us, primarily. He is writing for them. Because they are the ones whose clinical profile makes his silence dangerous — dangerous not because silence would be comfortable, but because their psychosis would read it as the one thing he will not give them.

The Broader Clinical Literature on Perpetrator Psychology
The perpetrator psychology Pearson is diagnosing has been documented across multiple contexts of state-sanctioned abuse, and the consent distortion appears consistently.
In Stanley Milgram’s obedience experiments, subjects who continued to administer what they believed were painful electric shocks to screaming victims did so in part because the institutional authority structure provided them with a framework in which the victim’s distress was interpreted as resistance to a legitimate procedure rather than evidence that the procedure should stop. The victim’s suffering was real. The perpetrator’s perception of it was filtered through a framework that converted suffering into non-compliance rather than into harm requiring cessation.
In Philip Zimbardo’s Stanford Prison Experiment — and more importantly in Zimbardo’s subsequent analysis of Abu Ghraib — the guards who inflicted humiliation and abuse on prisoners did not, in their own accounts, believe they were torturing. They believed they were managing unruly subjects. The prisoners’ distress was read not as evidence of harm but as evidence of the prisoners’ failure to cooperate with legitimate institutional procedure. The consent framework was total: a prisoner who accepted the institutional terms was a good prisoner. A prisoner who resisted was a problem prisoner whose resistance justified escalating pressure.
Martha Stout’s clinical work on sociopathy — specifically the one-in-twenty-five Americans she documents as lacking the capacity for genuine empathic response to others’ suffering — provides the individual-level clinical foundation for the institutional-level distortion Pearson describes. The person who runs a targeting program without apparent distress at what the program does to its targets is not necessarily performing a complex moral disengagement. They may simply lack the neurological substrate that would make the target’s suffering relevant to their own experience. Stout’s clinical profile of the sociopathic individual in a position of institutional authority — charming, functionally competent, genuinely incapable of the empathic response that would make their conduct feel wrong — maps precisely onto the type of person most likely to occupy the operational roles in a sustained targeting program.

Why Pearson Names It Psychosis Specifically
The word choice is deliberate and exact.
He does not say they are wrong. He does not say they are evil. He does not say they are operating in bad faith, or that they are lying to themselves, or that they are making a mistake. He says they are psychotic. And psychosis, clinically, means something specific: a condition in which the person’s internal model of reality has become sufficiently disconnected from reality that it cannot be corrected by evidence or argument. The person experiencing a psychotic delusion does not experience it as a delusion. They experience it as the truth. Evidence that contradicts the delusion is absorbed into the delusion — reinterpreted, discounted, or explained away — because the delusion is the framework through which all evidence is processed.
The perpetrators who would read Pearson’s silence as consent are not making a logical error they could be argued out of. They are operating from a fixed cognitive framework — the target who complies has been managed, the target who resists confirms the designation, the target who falls silent has been neutralized — that is impervious to the evidence of what is actually happening to him. His suffering is not evidence of harm because, within their framework, he is not a person whose suffering counts as harm. His documentation is not evidence of what he documents because, within their framework, it is a symptom of the pathology that justified the targeting. His silence would not be evidence of innocence because, within their framework, it would be evidence that the program worked.
This is the clinical definition of psychosis: a framework impervious to disconfirming evidence, maintained as reality regardless of what reality presents.
Pearson is living inside it. Not as a patient. As the object of it. He has to conduct himself — every day, in every decision about whether to write and what to say and how to document — with full awareness of the clinical profile of the people whose actions he is documenting. He has to understand their distortion well enough to communicate within it — to send them the only signal their framework can receive, which is the signal of ongoing resistance — while simultaneously maintaining, against the pressure that resistance produces, his own accurate account of what is happening.
That is the psychosis he is dealing with. Theirs. Applied to him. Every day.
And the sentence that names it is, in its quiet precision, an act of clinical observation as rigorous as anything in the medical literature — performed by a man diagnosing his torturers from inside the condition they have created for him.

Nazi Germany Called Holocaust a ‘State Secret’. What Does US Hide with Its ‘State Secrets’ Privilege?
Dr. Richard Pearson, US torture victim, calls upon secret US “Torture Dungeon” to close once and for all and for the Constitution to be restored. How many more victims are needed before the Congress and courts take action?
This is dedicated to Gloria Naylor, author of the Women of Brewster Place and 1996, whose rights and liberties were stripped from her in America’s Torture Dungeon. You were dismissed and ignored. I elevate you. It is also dedicated to all victims of US torture who have not been believed and received no justice.
In 1944, Nazi Germany produced a propaganda film, Theresienstadt, to mask the Holocaust. It showed Jews in a concentration camp, but not the horror of the camps that we know existed. No, this film manufactured a reality by forcing prisoners to watch or participate in live musical performances, in recreation, and sit at cafes. It was a lie entirely consistent with Nazi Germany’s efforts across Europe. Death camps became “re-education”. Execution became “special treatment”. We have failed to remember and learn from a key historical fact about the Holocaust.
Nazi Germany considered it a “state secret”
Officials produced as little written documentation as possible. That is not to say that many Europeans did not know what was happening. Many did. Americans even more so.
Within a decade after American troops encountered its first concentration camp in April 1945, the US adopted its own state secrets privilege. In United States v. Reynolds in 1953, the US Supreme Court allowed the government to block information in lawsuits that could damage national security. The government got to make that determination, and courts were required to defer to that judgment.
If the United States wanted a secret program to inflict harm, even death, on individual targets, minority populations, or the general public, it theoretically could claim state secrets privilege. Severe limitations to any civil suit. No judicial review of the merits of the claim. Erasure of constitutional rights.
That is what Reynolds set into motion.
Over the next three-quarters of a century, the US government continuously abused that privilege — not just abroad. Within its borders. Without interruption. It is still doing so. (See appendix). Mind control programs. Forced sterilization. Chemical torture. Bombing of civilian populations. Mass poisoning. Inducing psychosis. Financial and career sabotage. Withholding medical treatment. The use of weapons that the public has no knowledge exists and is technologically possible. We may never know the full extent of this abuse.
Like Nazi Germany, it employed propaganda throughout the modern postwar period. The US had tools that Nazi Germany never dreamt of to project a false reality. Wars of liberation. Leadership in internationalism and humanitarianism. American music. Film. Media. Immigration. The appearance of its commitment to the rule of law, human rights, civil liberties, civil rights, and constitutional democracy.
Theresienstadt.
This was the Upstairs. Not the Torture Dungeon. In the Upstairs, the Constitution mattered. Government conduct was transparent. Misconduct could be taken to a judge who could issue an injunction. Compensatory relief was available in some cases. Action taken against the government — from the filing of a civil complaint to a judge’s order — was publicly accessible. Paper trails. There were transparency and accountability.
But like Nazi Germany and Theresienstadt, the US held secrets. Broadly, it hid its Torture Dungeon.
The United States of America tortures. It needs to be said. It needs to be the lead story in every newspaper. It needs to appear on marquees. Torture is not, as it appears to the American public and the world, as periodic — rare moments of authoritarianism and totalitarianism. It is continuous. It is structural. The torture itself and the weapons are defined as “a state secret”. The shadow policies operate beyond congressional and judicial oversight — in the darkest corners of government and society. It occurs below, external to, and outside of the US Constitution. And if one examines the legal doctrines in the Upstairs closely enough, the clues were there all along — leading to the Torture Dungeon.
In invoking the state secrets privilege, the US severely limited the viability of a civil suit. Invoking national security can also be the death of a civil suit. Invoking Glomar — “neither confirm nor deny” — can be the death of a civil suit. Even if documents are turned over, redactions and withholding are common. If a victim makes rare progress through the courts after the government’s initial motion to dismiss, the judge could render the victims’ claims “frivolous” — meant to convey that victims are wasting the court’s time.
All of these and other legal doctrines had been there all along. Then there are the witnesses and whistleblowers.
Countless witnesses and whistleblowers can attest to the US Torture Dungeon. Most were not believed. Many remained in silence. Many more would not have understood the invisible campaigns involving classified technology, subtle or hidden players and tactics. They would have attributed their circumstances to their own choices and vulnerability. Their friends and families blamed the victims — their psychosis, their unfounded fear, and creative imagination.
The whistleblowers faced other challenges, “Over the last dozen years, whistleblowers at the National Security Agency have had a rough track record, facing FBI raids and lawsuits,” reported NPR in July 2014. The article continues, “(Bill) Binney says he and two other NSA colleagues who also quit tried sounding the alarm with congressional committees. But because they did not have documents to prove their charges, nobody believed them.”
When incidents of torture were eventually disclosed as MKUltra or COINTELPRO, they shocked the American public and resulted in new laws and layers of accountability. But the apparatus of state secret privilege was never dismantled. The Torture Dungeon maintained its structure, practices, tools, and secrecy.
The essay is about what happened when a government is given legal cover for a state secret. Not just any government — the United States of America. It focuses on one man — Richard Pearson who found himself in America’s secret Torture Dungeon.
There are rooms in the Torture Dungeon. Dr. Richard Pearson, an African American scholar, has been in several — all at once. The one that causes sleep deprivation. The one that induces fear due to sustained stalking and harassment. In one room, they enter his mind with a voice. Another steers him without his conscious control or awareness — taking over his cognition. Another uses spyware to hack his personal devices. One room engages in street theater to communicate threats, racial epithets, and totalitarian control and stalking. Each room aiming for personality destruction, social isolation, learned helplessness, and financial devastation.
“The United States of America is using “state secrets” privilege to torture in clear violation of the US Constitution and denies victims legal recourse by invoking “state secrets” in civil suits, forcing the courts to defer to that designation. If this is not a recipe for authoritarianism, I don’t know what is. Hitler and Nazi Germany proved that. Did the US learn from it? Hardly.” — Dr. Richard Pearson
Nazi Germany relied on its standing as a “civilized society” to rebut claims of torture. The US is also doing so. Gloria Naylor’s 1996 book strongly paralleled Dr. Pearson’s experience
I. What This Is
This is not a theoretical paper.
This is a documented account of what the United States government does to some of its citizens — specifically, to Black intellectuals of achievement and strong racial identity, to whistleblowers, to activists, to anyone whose intellectual production or political presence represents a specific and manageable threat to existing arrangements of power.
I am a PhD. I study equity. I have spent my professional life examining the gap between what institutions promise people and what they actually deliver. I have published peer-reviewed research. I have conducted community-based studies under real-world constraints, without funding, with methodological rigor appropriate to the research question.
I am also a man who has been tortured by his government in the capital city of the country that presents itself to the world as the standard of human rights and democratic governance.
These two facts are not in contradiction. They are, as I will demonstrate, structurally related.
The researcher and the researched are the same person. I name this explicitly because it is methodologically important. The knowledge I have about the dungeon — what I will call, throughout this paper, the domestic torture infrastructure of the American national security state — comes from the inside. From fourteen months of documented experience. From controlled observations, timestamped records, photographs, and a preemptive mental health evaluation obtained specifically to defeat an operational trap I understood was coming.
I am precise about all of this. Precision is what I have instead of legal remedy. Precision is what I have instead of institutional acknowledgment. Precision is, as I will show, the only tool that the dungeon cannot fully seal.

— -
II. Before the Dungeon: The World as It Was
I need to tell you who I was before this, because you cannot understand a destruction without first understanding what was there before the destroying began.
I was a researcher. I was a scholar. I had a life organized around the production of knowledge — the specific, methodologically grounded, peer-reviewed kind of knowledge that academic institutions recognize and reward. I had colleagues, students, professional relationships built across years of work. I had a home in Washington, DC, the most surveilled city in America, the city of lawyers and journalists and civil liberties organizations and congressional staffers and the entire above-ground apparatus of American constitutional democracy.
I had a bicycle.
I had a kitchen with a panini grill. It has a power button that I didn’t think could be removed.
I had a phone.
I had a mind that was entirely my own.
I am telling you this because the dungeon does not announce itself. It does not arrive with a warrant or a badge or any of the visible instruments of state power that the above-ground America has constructed to make government action legible, contestable, and subject to due process. It arrives looking exactly like the world. It arrives in the ordinary texture of daily life — a neighbor’s noise, traffic patterns, a misplaced object — and it works by converting the ordinary into the weaponized while maintaining the argument that nothing extraordinary is occurring.
This is its primary engineering achievement.
This is why I am going to be precise.
— -
III. The Arrival: A Man Named Meyerowitz
It begins with a man.
His name, as I came to know it, was David Meyerowitz. That was his surname. He, like his brother Bruce Morrow (“Cousin Brucie”), opted for a different last name. David appeared in Old Town Alexandria, Virginia — appeared is the correct word, because the quality of his arrival had the character of the prepared rather than the coincidental. I was reading a historical marker at an unremarkable building where David claimed to have an apartment for rent, “Do you know anyone looking for a room?” That the man might have known that I was behind in rent was not lost on me. He name-dropped. Donald Trump. Jared Kushner. The names deployed as currency, as demonstration of access, as the specific social performance of a person who wants you to know they move in circles where such names are ordinary.
I was not the kind of man to be impressed. To a billionaire, I would first ask, “How did you make your money?” To David, I might have asked, “Access to a President for what purpose? To serve whom? How?”
I am an equity scholar. I have spent my professional life studying the mechanisms through which power reproduces itself. I know a psychological assessment when I am inside one.
Something was wrong about Meyerowitz. I can give you the precise taxonomy of the wrongness — the endless storytelling, the repeated emphasis on his family helping Black people, the offense to his perception that I was unfamiliar with Kristallnacht, his nonprofit, his family’s escape from Nazi Germany with the help of Hitler’s number two. It was all too much.
As much as I was used to eccentric personalities being around the artists and artisans, David did not exhibit normal behavior. His arrival was too timed. His oversharing of family history irrelevant to the initial inquiry about renting. The “helping Black people” refrain. Having arrived at peak suspicion, I ripped the card and threw it in the trash. Did it have a tracking device?
There is another thing that you should know. David was not the only Jewish person whom I encountered. The woman who had followed me from Old Town Alexandria to Clarendon, Virginia on back-to-back days seemed Jewish. She stalked me with a “Bug Zapper” sign. I photographed her behind me. The man who appeared in Rockville at 6:30 am claiming to be looking for directions to an auction house that opened at 9 am. He appeared Jewish.

I did not understand this continuity. Frankly, where I grew up in the Deep South, we had two groups of people — white people and black people. I did not have much familiarity with Jewish people until after college. I found the Holocaust horrific. I still do. I find Holocaust deniers despicable. The Holocaust always resonated with me as an African American who knew US history of racism well. I heard more about Jewish traditions and storytelling. I enjoyed both. I believe that everyone should be treated with dignity and respect. All faiths that uphold equality, justice, and mercy should be embraced. Life is hard enough.
So, it deeply pained me that Gloria Naylor and I shared a similarity. Our initial campaign coincided with an encounter with a powerful Jewish person. For Gloria, Eunice Simon and Eunice’s brother who worked for the NSA. (She probably changed the names in her book for legal reasons.) For me, David Meyerowitz who name-dropped Donald Trump and Jared Kushner. After reading Gloria’s account, it makes me question the NSA connection to my torture. It is unfortunate.
— -
IV. The Ceiling
The first thing I need to explain about the dungeon is that it looks exactly like the world.
My ceiling looks like a ceiling. White. Flat. The ordinary construction of a residential building in Washington, DC.
But my ceiling has a person above it.
And that person knows where I am at all times.
The sounds begin at night. Not the sounds of ordinary habitation — the ambient noise of neighbors living their lives in a building designed for multiple occupants. Targeted sounds. Deliberate sounds. Sounds that follow me.
I moved my mattress to the closet. I did this deliberately, as a researcher testing a hypothesis I did not want confirmed.
The sounds moved to the closet.
Directly above me. Above the specific square footage I was occupying. Above my body in the closet, which no person should know is in the closet — no person who does not have a real-time capability to locate a body within an apartment, which is a capability that exists, which has been documented in both classified and unclassified literature, which was used against me on the floor of my own closet at three in the morning in the capital of the United States of America. Gloria Naylor’s 1996 also discussed similar campaigns of noise harassment.
I am a researcher. I conduct control studies. I lay in the closet and I conducted a control study on my own ceiling.
