FEMA / Pentagon “Continuity of Government” radiological preparedness experiments — Post-Katrina evidence of civilian population radiological exposure modeling that treated urban populations as modeling variables.

II. Mind Control, Psychological Torture & Behavioral Weaponization
Project CHATTER (1947–1953) — U.S. Navy program testing mescaline and other drugs as truth serums on human subjects, inspired directly by Nazi experiments.
Project BLUEBIRD / ARTICHOKE (1950–1956) — CIA programs using hypnosis, barbiturates, amphetamines, and physical coercion to produce amnesia, false confessions, and programmable behavior. Conducted on prisoners, mental patients, and foreign nationals.
MKUltra (1953–1973) — 150+ subprojects across 80 institutions including 44 universities, 15 research foundations, 12 hospitals, and 3 prisons. Used LSD, heroin, mescaline, methamphetamine, electroconvulsive therapy, sensory deprivation, hypnosis, verbal and sexual abuse, and induced trauma. Most records destroyed by CIA Director Richard Helms in 1973. At least two known deaths: Frank Olson (thrown from a 13th-floor window) and Harold Blauer (lethal mescaline injection).
Ewen Cameron / MKULTRA Subproject 68 (Montreal, 1957–1964) — CIA-funded psychiatrist at McGill University subjected patients to chemically-induced sleep for weeks or months, massive electroshock (30–40x standard dose), drug cocktails, and psychic driving (looped audio messages played through helmets). Patients arrived with mild depression; many emerged with complete amnesia, permanent regression to childlike states, and destroyed identities. Canada paid reparations; the U.S. did not.
Operation Paperclip (1945–1959) — Over 1,600 Nazi scientists, engineers, and physicians — including SS officers and those who conducted experiments at Dachau and Auschwitz — recruited by the U.S. government, given new identities, and integrated into military and intelligence programs. War crimes records were falsified.
Subproject 54 (“Black Witch”) — Studied inducing concussions and amnesia through non-detectable means; no known survivors identified.
Project OFTEN (1962–1973) — CIA and Army study of occultism, drug-induced states, and exotic toxins as means of behavioral control.
Psychic Driving on Veterans (VA hospitals, 1950s–60s) — Techniques developed under Cameron were replicated at U.S. VA hospitals on veterans without consent.
Sensory deprivation research (McGill, NIMH, CIA funding) — Isolation tank and sensory deprivation experiments developed into SERE (Survival, Evasion, Resistance, Escape) training and later reverse-engineered into CIA “enhanced interrogation” techniques post-9/11.
SERE reverse-engineering (2001–2007) — The DOD’s JPRA (Joint Personnel Recovery Agency) reversed SERE training — designed to help soldiers resist torture — into an active torture program. Psychologists James Mitchell and Bruce Jessen, contracted by the CIA, designed the program and were paid $81 million.

III. Biological & Medical Experimentation Without Consent
Tuskegee Syphilis Study (1932–1972) — 399 Black men with syphilis in Macon County, Alabama were studied by the U.S. Public Health Service for 40 years. They were told they were being treated for “bad blood,” actively denied penicillin after it became the standard cure in 1947, and followed to autopsy. When discovered by journalist Jean Heller in 1972, 28 men had died of syphilis, 100 of complications, 40 wives were infected, and 19 children were born with congenital syphilis.
Guatemala STD experiments (1946–1948) — U.S. PHS researchers deliberately infected Guatemalan prisoners, psychiatric patients, soldiers, orphans, and sex workers with syphilis, gonorrhea, and chancroid — sometimes through open wounds — without any consent. Approximately 1,300 people infected; 83 confirmed deaths. Funded by the NIH; concealed until 2010.
Willowbrook Hepatitis experiments (1956–1970) — Children with intellectual disabilities at Willowbrook State School on Staten Island were deliberately infected with hepatitis to study disease progression and vaccine candidates. Parents were coerced into consent by threatening to deny their children admission.
Stateville Penitentiary Malaria Study (1944–1946) — Hundreds of Illinois inmates infected with malaria. Researchers included Nathan Leopold of the Leopold and Loeb case.
Holmesburg Prison experiments (1951–1974) — Dermatologist Albert Kligman (later famous for inventing Retin-A) conducted hundreds of experiments on Philadelphia prisoners: dioxin exposure, radioactive isotope injections, psychoactive drug testing for the Army, carcinogen patch tests for Dow Chemical, and pathogen inoculations for Johnson & Johnson. Kligman reportedly said on first entering Holmesburg: “All I saw before me were acres of skin.”
Fernald State School experiments (1946–1953) — MIT researchers fed radioactive iron and calcium to intellectually disabled children in oatmeal, funded by the Atomic Energy Commission and Quaker Oats, to study nutrient absorption. Parents were told children were joining a “science club.”
Vanderbilt Nutrition Study (1945–1946) — Pregnant low-income women given radioactive iron cocktails by Vanderbilt University without informed consent; several children later developed cancer.
VA electroshock and drug experiments (1950s–1970s) — Veterans used as experimental subjects for antipsychotics, LSD, and electroconvulsive therapy without informed consent at multiple VA hospitals.
DOD LSD field tests on soldiers (1950s–60s) — Thousands of military personnel administered LSD without knowledge in Army Chemical Corps experiments at Edgewood Arsenal; others given BZ (a powerful hallucinogen) and nerve agents including VX and GB.
Edgewood Arsenal experiments (1948–1975) — 7,000 U.S. soldiers exposed to over 250 chemical agents: nerve agents, blister agents, psychoactive compounds, and riot control agents.
Syphilis experiments on Guatemalan orphans — Children in Catholic orphanages used as infection vectors; nuns reported some were used repeatedly.
CDC “Let Them Eat Cake” lead paint studies (2001) — Johns Hopkins Kennedy Krieger Institute intentionally placed Black children in homes with known varying lead paint levels to study abatement thresholds, without disclosing risk to families. A Maryland court compared it to Tuskegee.
COVID-19 prison experiments — During the pandemic, federal and state prisons maintained infection conditions that functioned as involuntary exposure studies, with outcomes tracked by public health systems.
Unethical pharmaceutical trials on incarcerated populations (ongoing) — Despite post-Nuremberg reforms, prison pharmaceutical testing continued through the 1970s and loopholes allow ongoing exploitation of captive populations.

IV. Forced Sterilization & Reproductive Violence
Eugenic sterilization under state laws (1907–1970s) — Thirty-three states enacted compulsory sterilization statutes. The Buck v. Bell (1927) Supreme Court decision upheld them; Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes wrote “three generations of imbeciles are enough.” Approximately 60,000–65,000 Americans sterilized — disproportionately poor, immigrant, disabled, and Black.
California’s eugenic program — The most aggressive in the nation: approximately 20,000 people sterilized, providing a model that Nazi physicians explicitly studied and cited.
Puerto Rican mass sterilization / “La Operación” (1930s–1970s) — U.S.-administered program resulted in roughly one-third of Puerto Rican women being sterilized, often through coercion, misinformation, or without understanding the permanence of the procedure. By 1968, Puerto Rico had the highest per-capita sterilization rate in the world.
Native American sterilization via Indian Health Service (1970–1976) — A GAO investigation revealed the IHS sterilized 3,406 Native women in a four-year period in just four of twelve service areas; broader estimates range from 25,000 to 50,000 women sterilized during the decade. Many were minors; many signed consent forms during labor under threat of losing welfare benefits or child custody.
North Carolina Eugenics Board (1929–1974) — Among the most aggressive state programs; operated until 1974, targeting Black women and girls. North Carolina became the first state to pay reparations ($10 million) to survivors in 2013.
California prison sterilizations (2006–2010) — At least 148 female inmates at Valley State Prison and California Institution for Women were sterilized, many without proper informed consent. A state audit confirmed “deficiencies” in the consent process. No criminal charges were filed.
ICE detention sterilizations (2020) — Whistleblower Dawn Wooten alleged a gynecologist at the Irwin County Detention Center in Georgia was performing hysterectomies on immigrant women at an extraordinary rate, often without clear informed consent or medical necessity. Congressional investigations confirmed high rates of unexplained procedures.
Mississippi appendectomy — The informal practice of performing unnecessary hysterectomies on Black women in Southern teaching hospitals for medical student training; named and described by Fannie Lou Hamer, who was herself sterilized without consent in 1961.

V. Domestic Surveillance, Political Repression & Infiltration
COINTELPRO (1956–1971) — The FBI’s Counter Intelligence Program targeted the Communist Party, Socialist Workers Party, Puerto Rican independence movement, American Indian Movement, Black Panther Party, Nation of Islam, SCLC, SNCC, and antiwar organizations. Tactics included: informant infiltration, forged letters to incite internal conflict, “snitch-jacketing” (falsely labeling members as informants to provoke violence), blackmail, fabricated evidence, and coordination with local police to conduct raids. Fred Hampton, 21-year-old Black Panther chairman, was killed in a pre-dawn FBI-coordinated raid while asleep; internal documents later revealed the FBI paid the informant who provided the floor plan.
FBI surveillance and harassment of Martin Luther King Jr. — Wiretapped for years; J. Edgar Hoover called him “the most dangerous Negro in America.” The FBI sent King an anonymous letter explicitly urging him to commit suicide days before he received the Nobel Peace Prize. The Senate Church Committee later called this “one of the most shameful chapters in the history of the Bureau.”
Operation CHAOS (CIA, 1967–1974) — Illegal CIA domestic surveillance of over 7,200 American citizens and 1,000 organizations including antiwar groups, civil rights organizations, and journalists. Created a database of 300,000 names.
HTLINGUAL / Mail Opening Program (1953–1973) — CIA and FBI opened, photographed, and resealed first-class mail of American citizens for 20 years. Over 215,000 letters were opened; targets included senators, congressmen, businessmen, and artists.
Operation SHAMROCK (1945–1975) — NSA intercepted every international telegram sent from or to the United States, with cooperation from RCA, ITT, and Western Union. Three major companies handed over millions of cables daily for 30 years.
Operation MINARET (1967–1973) — NSA watchlist-based surveillance of American antiwar activists, Black Power leaders, and journalists, including Muhammad Ali, Jane Fonda, Dr. Benjamin Spock, Senator Frank Church, and journalists.
Red Squads (1900s–1990s) — Municipal police intelligence units in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, and elsewhere operated decades-long infiltration and harassment operations against labor unions, socialist organizations, civil rights groups, and LGBTQ+ organizations. The NYPD’s BOSSI (Bureau of Special Services) had files on over one million people.
NSA STELLARWIND / PRISM / XKeyscore (2001–present) — Post-9/11 bulk collection of domestic phone metadata, email content, internet browsing history, and social media data without individual warrants, revealed by Edward Snowden in 2013. The FISA Court later ruled the phone metadata program illegal.
FBI “Black Identity Extremist” (BIE) designation (2017) — The FBI created a fabricated domestic terrorism category to justify surveillance of Black activists in the post-Ferguson era, with no statutory basis and no criminal conduct required for targeting.
Muslim community surveillance (NYPD Demographics Unit, post-9/11) — NYPD’s Intelligence Division, with CIA assistance, conducted mass surveillance of Muslim communities across the Northeast, mapping mosques, restaurants, schools, and student groups with no predicate criminal activity. Revealed by the AP in 2011.
Fusion Centers surveillance overreach — Post-9/11 “terrorism fusion centers” across all 50 states compiled intelligence on political demonstrators, environmental activists, veterans’ groups, and Tea Party organizations with no criminal nexus.
Joint Terrorism Task Force targeting of climate activists — FBI JTTF infiltrated and designated environmental activists (including Standing Rock water protectors) as domestic terrorists while coordinating with pipeline companies.
Chicago Police Homan Square black site — Off-the-books interrogation facility operated by the Chicago Police Department where detainees were held incommunicado, shackled to walls, denied access to lawyers, and in some cases subjected to physical coercion. The Guardian documented over 7,000 detainees processed through the site.

VI. Torture, Detention & Rendition
Operation Phoenix (Vietnam, 1965–1972) — CIA-designed program that tortured, “neutralized,” and assassinated an estimated 20,000–40,000 Vietnamese civilians suspected of supporting the NLF. William Colby, later CIA director, acknowledged before Congress that many killed were not proven combatants. Techniques included waterboarding (called “the water treatment”), electric shock, and the “tiger cages” at Con Son prison.
School of the Americas / WHINSEC (Fort Benning, 1946–present) — U.S. military training institution whose graduates include some of the most documented torturers and death squad commanders in Latin American history: Roberto D’Aubuisson (El Salvador death squads), Hugo Banzer (Bolivian dictator), Manuel Noriega, Leopoldo Galtieri (Argentina’s Dirty War). In 1996, the Pentagon was forced to release training manuals that explicitly recommended torture, blackmail, and execution. Over 60,000 Latin American military officers trained.
Operation Condor (1975–1989) — U.S. State Department and CIA coordinated intelligence sharing, operational support, and logistics for a network of South American dictatorships — Argentina, Chile, Uruguay, Paraguay, Bolivia, Brazil — that disappeared, tortured, and murdered an estimated 60,000 people, including American citizens. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger authorized U.S. participation; his cables were declassified in 2001.
Abu Ghraib (2003–2004) — Systematic torture, sexual humiliation, rape, and murder of Iraqi detainees by U.S. military personnel. The Taguba Report confirmed these were not isolated incidents but the product of command climate, intelligence directives, and private contractor involvement (CACI International). Only low-ranking soldiers were prosecuted.
CIA “Enhanced Interrogation” Program / Black Sites (2001–2007) — Senate Intelligence Committee report (2014) documented that the CIA subjected at least 119 detainees to: waterboarding (Khalid Sheikh Mohammed 183 times), “rectal rehydration” without medical justification (acknowledged as a control technique), sleep deprivation for up to 180 hours in stress positions, walling, confinement in small boxes, mock executions, threats to rape and murder detainees’ family members, hypothermia, and “rough takedowns.” The program produced no unique intelligence not obtainable through legal means, according to the Committee’s findings. The CIA misled Congress and the White House about the program’s scope and effectiveness.
Guantánamo Bay (2002–present) — Over 780 people detained; the majority released without charge. Ongoing indefinite detention without trial for remaining detainees. Documented force-feeding of hunger strikers (recognized as cruel and degrading treatment under international law), prolonged isolation, and religious humiliation. Military commissions have produced fewer than a dozen convictions.
Extraordinary Rendition Program — CIA abducted individuals from at least 54 countries and transported them to third-party nations (Egypt, Syria, Morocco, Uzbekistan, Thailand) known to practice torture. German citizen Khaled El-Masri was kidnapped by mistake, held and tortured for five months; the CIA knew within a month he was the wrong person and held him anyway.
Drone assassination program / Targeted killing (2001–present) — Over 14,000 U.S. drone strikes across Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Yemen, Somalia, Pakistan, and Libya. Bureau of Investigative Journalism estimates 8,000–16,000 civilian deaths. The Obama administration’s “signature strike” program authorized killing unidentified individuals based on behavioral patterns (“military-age males” in “conflict zones”). The kill list (“disposition matrix”) was reviewed by the President in weekly meetings. No judicial oversight; no due process. American citizens Anwar al-Awlaki and his 16-year-old son Abdulrahman were killed in separate strikes; neither was charged with a crime.
JSOC assassination and detention networks — Joint Special Operations Command operated parallel detention facilities in Iraq (“Camp Nama”) and Afghanistan with documented use of torture, sleep deprivation, and homicide. Operated outside the Army Field Manual and the Geneva Conventions.
Manning, Torture by Isolation (2010–2011) — Chelsea Manning was held in solitary confinement at Quantico for 11 months under conditions a United Nations Special Rapporteur on Torture formally called “cruel, inhumane, and degrading.” Manning was kept in a 6x8 foot cell 23 hours per day, forced to stand naked during inspections, and denied meaningful human contact.

VII. Indigenous Peoples: Genocide, Cultural Destruction & Ongoing Dispossession
Federal Indian boarding schools (1869–1970s) — Over 400 federally funded schools forcibly removed an estimated 150,000 Native children from their families. Children were forbidden to speak their languages, practice their religions, wear traditional clothing, or use their Native names under penalty of physical punishment. Sexual, physical, and psychological abuse was widespread and systemic. A 2022 Interior Department investigation identified at least 53 burial sites at former school properties.
Carlisle Indian Industrial School — The model institution under Richard Pratt, whose stated philosophy was “Kill the Indian, save the man.” Children were regularly worked as unpaid agricultural and domestic labor, “leased out” to white families, and subjected to military-style discipline and physical punishment. Death rates were high; Carlisle’s cemetery holds the remains of children who died far from home.
Termination Policy (1953–1968) — Congress unilaterally terminated federal recognition of over 100 tribes, ending trust protections and forcing the sale of tribal lands. 1.4 million acres of Indian land were lost. Health services, education funding, and treaty rights were stripped.
Relocation Program (1950s–1960s) — Federal program relocated approximately 100,000 Native Americans from reservations to cities (Chicago, Los Angeles, Denver, San Francisco) with promises of housing and jobs that rarely materialized, creating urban poverty and disconnecting people from their communities and support systems.
Water rights theft and dam construction — Federal dam projects flooded the homelands of dozens of nations without consent: Garrison Dam (Three Affiliated Tribes, 1953), Kinzua Dam (Seneca Nation, 1960s), Tellico Dam (Cherokee, 1979). Over 1 million acres of tribal land flooded.
Uranium mining on Navajo Nation (1944–1986) — 4 million tons of uranium ore extracted from Navajo land using Navajo workers who were never told of radiation risks. Hundreds of abandoned mine sites remain unreclaimed. Diné communities continue to suffer elevated rates of cancer, kidney disease, and birth defects. EPA cleanup has been slow and incomplete for decades.
DAPL / Standing Rock (2016–2017) — U.S. Army Corps of Engineers rerouted the Dakota Access Pipeline from north of Bismarck (rejected due to proximity to the city’s water supply) to directly under the Missouri River, above the Standing Rock Sioux reservation’s water supply. Water protectors — peaceful protesters — were subjected to water cannons in sub-zero temperatures, rubber bullets, acoustic weapons, mass arrest, and FBI/JTTF surveillance.
Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women (MMIW) — Indigenous women are murdered at 10 times the national average. FBI case files show extraordinary non-prosecution rates. The National Crime Information Center has no specific category for MMIW cases, making the scope systematically unmeasurable. Many perpetrators operate with impunity on the jurisdictional boundaries between tribal, state, and federal authority.
Forced relocation of Diné (Navajo-Hopi Land Dispute, 1970s–present) — Over 12,000 Navajo people forcibly relocated from Big Mountain / Black Mesa in what has been called by some human rights scholars the largest forced relocation of Native Americans since the Trail of Tears, driven by competing energy extraction interests.

